    <chapter id="reference-data-types-in-c">
        <title>
            <control>Reference Data Types in C#</control>
        </title>
        <p>In C#,
            <control>reference data types</control>
            are types that store references (or pointers) to the actual data rather than the data itself. When you
            assign a reference type variable to another variable, they both point to the same memory location, meaning
            they share the same data.
        </p>
        <p>Reference types are stored in the
            <control>heap</control>
            memory, and variables of reference types hold the memory address (reference) of where the data is stored,
            not the actual data. This is different from
            <control>value types</control>
            (like <code>int</code>, <code>float</code>, etc.), which store the actual data in memory.
        </p>
    </chapter>
